Exercise 2.3

Part A

This isn’t a binomial probability; there’s not a fixed number of trials OR only two possible outcomes (there are infinite possible outcomes, as theoretically ANY amount of babies could be born between 9 and 10am tomorrow).

Part B

Yes! Y is binomial, because there’s a fixed number of trials (27 planted tulips) and only two possible outcomes (blooms or doesn’t). \[f(y|\pi = .9) = \binom{27}{y} .9^{y} (1-.9)^{27-y} \text{ for } y \in \{1, 2, 3, ... 27\} \]

Part C

Yes, you can model this using a binomial probability, except instead of the number of successes being unknown, the number of trials is unknown. \[f(y|\pi = .17|k = 1) = \binom{y}{1} .17^{1} (1-.17)^{y-1} \]

Part D

This is not a binomial, because there are more outcomes than simply success or failure (there are infinitely many outcomes, because he could be infinitely many minutes late).

Part E

This isn’t a binomial probability either…I’m not sure why to be completely honest, it’s just a gut feeling.

Part F

This one is a binomial probability! \[f(y|\pi = .8) = \binom{60}{y} .8^{y} (1-.8)^{60-y} \text{ for } y \in \{1, 2, 3, ... 60\} \]

Exercise 2.4

post odds = prior odds * likelihood ratio

prior odds = 5/95 = 1/19

likelihood ratio = .7 / .03 = 23.333

post odds = (1/19) * 23.333 = 23.333 / 19

post probability = 23.333 / (19 + 23.333) = .551 = 55.1%

Exercise 2.5

Part A

\[P(\text{mold}) = .18 = 18\% \]

Part B

\[ P(\text{maple}) = P(\text{maple} \cap \text{diseased}) + P(\text{maple} \cap \text{healthy}) = (.18)(.80) + (.82)(.10) = .226 = 22.6\% \]

Part C

prior odds = .18/.82 = 9/41

likelihood ratio = .80/.10 = 8

post odds = 9/41 * 8 = 72/41

post probability = 72/(41+72) = .637 = 63.7%

Part D

The posterior probability is higher than the prior, which makes sense since the majority of infected trees were maples and only a small percentage of the healthy trees were maples, so intuitively it’s more likely that a maple tree is diseased than healthy. However, it also makes sense that the post probability isn’t extremely high, because a low percentage of the trees in the orchard are actually diseased.

prior <- c(.25, .6, .15)
likelihood <- choose(6,4)*(pi^4)*((1-pi)^2)
normconstant <- sum(likelihood*prior)
posterior <- prior * likelihood / normconstant

Exercise 2.12

Part A

\[f(y|\pi) = \binom{7}{y} \pi^{y} (1-\pi)^{7-y} \text{ for } y \in \{1, 2, 3, ... 7\} \]

Part B

\[f(\pi|y = 1) = 7\pi(1-\pi)^{6}\]

The updated model would be as follows:

pi2 <- c(.1,.25,.4)
prior2 <- c(.2, .45, .35)
likelihood2 <- 7*(pi2)*((1-pi2)^6)
normconstant2 <- sum(likelihood2*prior2)
posterior2 <- prior2 * likelihood2 / normconstant2
data.frame(pi2, posterior2)
##    pi2 posterior2
## 1 0.10  0.2858497
## 2 0.25  0.5384840
## 3 0.40  0.1756662

Part C

The posterior model seems to be leaning towards lower values of pi than the prior, which makes sense since the data point we factored in was that he only made 1 of 7 good handles, so we would expect him to be a worse ceramics guy than we thought before.

Part D

Kris’s updated model is as follows:

pi3 <- c(.1,.25,.4)
prior3 <- c(.15, .15, .7)
likelihood3 <- 7*(pi3)*((1-pi3)^6)
normconstant3 <- sum(likelihood3*prior3)
posterior3 <- prior3 * likelihood3 / normconstant3
data.frame(pi3, posterior3)
##    pi3 posterior3
## 1 0.10  0.2876854
## 2 0.25  0.2408631
## 3 0.40  0.4714515

Kris’s posterior was less affected by the new data, at least in terms of overall shape of the probability distribution, which makes sense because his prior model was more extreme, and so would be harder to affect with new data.

Exercise 2.20

cat <- data.frame(type = c("cat", "not cat"))
prior <- c(0.08, 0.92)
set.seed(18)
cat_sim <- sample_n(cat, size = 10000, 
                        weight = prior, replace = TRUE)

cat_sim <- cat_sim |>  
  mutate(algorithm_model = case_when(type == "cat" ~ 0.8,
                                type == "not cat" ~ 0.5))

algresult <- c("yes a cat", "not a cat")

cat_sim <- cat_sim |> 
  group_by(1:n()) |>  
  mutate(algorithm = sample(algresult, size = 1, 
                        prob = c(algorithm_model, 1-algorithm_model)))

cat_sim |>  
  tabyl(algorithm, type) |>  
  adorn_totals(c("col","row"))
##  algorithm cat not cat Total
##  not a cat 148    4619  4767
##  yes a cat 626    4607  5233
##      Total 774    9226 10000
626/5233
## [1] 0.1196255

The probability that an image is a cat if the algorithm says it’s a cat is 12%.

Exercise 2.21

disease <- data.frame(health = c("sick", "not sick"))
prior <- c(.03,.97)
set.seed(18)
disease_sim <- sample_n(disease, size=10000, weight = prior, replace=TRUE)

disease_sim |> 
  tabyl(health) |> 
  adorn_totals("row")
##    health     n percent
##  not sick  9718  0.9718
##      sick   282  0.0282
##     Total 10000  1.0000
disease_sim <- disease_sim |>
  mutate(testresult_model = case_when(health == "sick" ~.93,
                                      health == "not sick" ~.07))

possibleresult <- c("positive", "negative")

disease_sim <- disease_sim |> 
  group_by(1:n()) |> mutate(testresult = sample(possibleresult, size=1,
                          prob = c(testresult_model, 1-testresult_model)))

disease_sim |> 
  tabyl(health, testresult) |> 
  adorn_totals("row", "col")
##    health negative positive
##  not sick     9017      701
##      sick       20      262
##     Total     9037      963
262/963
## [1] 0.2720665

The probability that someone has the disease given that they tested positive is 27.2%.
